    en: "New York charges mortgage recording tax (Tax Law Article 11) on every new mortgage recorded — typically about 1 percent of the mortgage amount on a Monroe County residential property. When a homeowner refinances, a Consolidation, Extension, and Modification Agreement (CEMA) preserves the original mortgage's recorded status and limits the mortgage recording tax to the difference between the new loan amount and the unpaid balance of the old loan. Tax Law Section 255 authorizes this supplemental-mortgage exemption by affidavit. A homeowner refinancing a $250,000 balance into a new $250,000 mortgage pays roughly $50 in recording-tax adjustment using a CEMA, versus approximately $2,500 without one — a $2,450 savings. Many lenders charge a $500-$1,500 CEMA processing fee. The math makes CEMA worthwhile on balances above about $100,000."
