    en: "A Pittsford homeowner refinanced her 30-year fixed-rate mortgage in 2024. Existing balance: $310,000 at 7.25 percent. New loan: $310,000 at 5.75 percent, same lender. She asked her loan officer specifically about a CEMA at the application stage. The same-lender CEMA fee was $450 built into closing costs. The Section 255 affidavit certified the supplemental mortgage for the entire $310,000 existing principal, so the only mortgage recording tax at closing was on the $1 technical Gap Note — approximately $0.02 of tax. Without CEMA, Monroe County's approximately 1 percent mortgage recording tax on $310,000 would have been $3,075 minus the $25 residential credit = $3,050 out of pocket. CEMA net savings: $3,050 - $450 = $2,600. The savings effectively paid for six months of the new mortgage's lower rate. Had she not asked about CEMA, the loan officer would have processed the refinance as a new mortgage and charged her the full recording tax."
